The LCD control system using a potentiometer and temperature sensor is a project that involves using an Arduino board to read temperature from a temperature sensor and display it on an LCD screen. The system also uses a potentiometer to control the brightness of the LCD panel.

To set up the system, the temperature sensor, such as the DS18B20 or LM35, is connected to the Arduino board. The analog output pin of the temperature sensor is connected to an analog input pin on the Arduino board, such as pin A0 [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)]. The LCD screen is connected to the Arduino board via a LiquidCrystal I2C library, which can be installed through the Arduino IDE [[1](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-temperature-sensor-lcd)].

The potentiometer is used to control the brightness of the LCD panel. One pin of the potentiometer is connected to the VCC pin on the Arduino board, while the other pin is connected to pin 3 on the LCD screen [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

To program the Arduino board, the LiquidCrystal I2C library is used to control the LCD screen, and the temperature sensor code is combined with the LCD code to display the temperature reading on the LCD screen [[1](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-temperature-sensor-lcd)]. The code can be uploaded to the Arduino board using the Arduino IDE.

Overall, the LCD control system using a potentiometer and temperature sensor is a useful project for learning how to use Arduino to read temperature and display it on an LCD screen, while also controlling the brightness of the LCD panel using a potentiometer.

To support Azure Active Directory (AAD) Single Sign-On (SSO) tokens in Apache Airflow, you'll need to configure the `auth_backend` and `auth_type` settings in your `airflow.cfg` file.

Here's an example configuration code snippet that you can use as a starting point:
```python
[core]
auth_backend = airflow.contrib.auth.backends.azure_active_directory

[azure_active_directory]
client_id = <your_client_id>
client_secret = <your_client_secret>
tenant_id = <your_tenant_id>
authority = https://login.microsoftonline.com/<your_tenant_id>
token_endpoint = https://login.microsoftonline.com/<your_tenant_id>/oauth2/v2.0/token
```
Replace the placeholders with your actual Azure AD application settings:

* `client_id`: The client ID of your Azure AD application.
* `client_secret`: The client secret of your Azure AD application.
* `tenant_id`: The tenant ID of your Azure AD application.

You'll also need to install the `azure-identity` and `azure-common` libraries, which are required by the `airflow.contrib.auth.backends.azure_active_directory` backend. You can install them using pip:
```bash
pip install azure-identity azure-common
```
Once you've updated your `airflow.cfg` file and installed the required libraries, restart your Airflow webserver and scheduler to apply the changes.
